What does Polarization Look Like in American Politics?

An Exploratory Data Analysis

by: Natalie Williams

naw2127@columbia.edu

I. Introduction

You may have heard the phrase Political Polarization in the news recently. A New York Times article described polarization as a National Security Threat. link Further, Americans surveyed by the Chicago Council Survey of American Public and US Foreign Policy placed political polarization within the top five critical threats to the US. link While in January 2020, CNN reported that political polarization was at a 74 year high, citing an 82 point gap between Republican approval of Trump and Democratic. link

How is Political Polarization Defined?

The Pew Research Center, a highly respected nonpartisan fact tank, defines Political Polarization as the following: > Political Polarization conceptually represents some kind of aggregated ideological differences between parties.

How do Political Scientists Measure It?

WIkipedia- Some political scientists assert that contemporary polarization depends less on policy differences on a left and right scale, but increasingly on other divisions such as: religious against secular; nationalist against globalist; traditional against modern; rural against urban.[19]

*II. Methodology ** To find what polarization looks like in the US, survey results collected by the American National Election Studies(ANES) link, will be investigated.

What Do Democrats and Republicans Think about Illegal Aliens Over Time

library(ggrepel)
load(file="output/all_Democrats.RData")
load(file="output/all_Republicans.RData")

`%out%` <- function(a,b) ! a %in% b

demIA <- all_Democrats%>%
  select(year, illegalAliens)%>%
  filter(!is.na(illegalAliens))%>%
  filter(illegalAliens %out% c("98. DK  (exc. 1964-1968: see VCF0201 note)",
                               "99. NA; no Post IW; form III,IV (1972); breakoff,   sufficient partial (2016)"))%>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  mutate(
    Average = mean(as.numeric(illegalAliens))
  )%>%
  distinct(year, .keep_all=TRUE)

# Republicans now 
repIA <- all_Republicans%>%
  select(year, illegalAliens)%>%
  filter(!is.na(illegalAliens))%>%
  filter(illegalAliens %out% c("98. DK  (exc. 1964-1968: see VCF0201 note)",
                               "99. NA; no Post IW; form III,IV (1972); breakoff,   sufficient partial (2016)"))%>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  mutate(
    Average = mean(as.numeric(illegalAliens))
  )%>%
  distinct(year, .keep_all=TRUE)

IA <- data.frame(
  demIA$year, demIA$Average, repIA$Average
)%>%
  rename(
    Year = demIA.year,
    Democrat_Average = demIA.Average,
    Republican_Average = repIA.Average
  )%>%
  mutate(
    Percent_Difference = 2*(Democrat_Average - Republican_Average)/(Democrat_Average+Republican_Average)  
    )



IAplot <- IA%>%
  mutate(
    labelDem =if_else(Year==last(IA$Year),
                      true = as.character(round(last(IA$Democrat_Average), digits = 1)),
                      false= ""
    ),
    labelRep =if_else(Year==last(IA$Year),
                      true = as.character(round(last(IA$Republican_Average), digits = 1)),
                      false= ""
    )
  )%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_line(aes(x= Year, y= Democrat_Average, group=1), color="blue")+
  geom_line(aes(x= Year, y= Republican_Average, group=2), color="red")+
  geom_label_repel(aes(label=labelDem, x = Year, y=Democrat_Average))+
  geom_label_repel(aes(label=labelRep, x = Year, y=Republican_Average))+
  ylab("Average Warmness Towards Illegal Aliens/ Immigrants")+
  ylim(0,100)+
  xlab("Year")

#ggsave(path="figs", filename="illegalAlienPlot.png")  
print(IAplot)
